               <lb/><milestone unit="phrase" edRef="S-11"/>summer–as if not till then was <lb/>their
               beauty ripe.— wild oats <w>per<lb/>chance</w> and life-everlasting whose <lb/>autumn
               has now arrived–those <w>un<lb/>exhausted</w> granaries of winter, whose <lb/>seeds
               entertain the earliest birds. <lb/>I never tire of admiring their <lb/>arching
               drooping and sheaflike tops <lb/>They bring back the summer to our<lb/> winter
               memories–and are among<lb/> the forms which art loves to <w>perpetu-<lb/>ate</w>.
               They are an antique style–older <lb/>than Greek or Egyptian–a lighter <lb/>and more
               graceful Ionic– <!-- NW: Here we have used a listTrasnpose element within a mod element to 
               record the transpositions that are indicated by Thoreau's markings upon the 
               underlying flow of the text as it appears on the page. The underlying text is
               transcribed in the order in which it occurs on the page, but where T has 
               indicated the chunks of the text he intended to transpose after their initial 
               inscription using a transposition metamark, we have wrapped the separate parts
               of the transposition in seg elements, the intended (rather than inscribed) order
               of which are recorded as a list of transpose elements, pointing to the associated
               seg elements with @n values that match the transpose@target values. -->
               <mod>
                  <seg n="01">a <w>ric<metamark rend="number" place="above">2</metamark>her</w>
                     <lb/>Corinthian–</seg><metamark rend="transposition"/>
                  <seg n="02">a <w>simp<metamark rend="number" place="below">1</metamark>ler</w>
                     Doric</seg>
                  <listTranspose>
                     <!-- If we always transcribe text as it appears on the page, regardless of the 
                        indicated transpositions, we could probably drop the transpose element that
                        simply lists the initial ordering, as it is implied. In that case, we only 
                        need to indicate later (i.e. after initial inline inscription) transpositions.
                        If we want to keep all orderings in this list, I think we should add some kind
                        of typology or ordering info in the form of an attribute in the transpose elements
                        such that we distinguish between the transpositions being recorded more explicitly
                       than simply putting them in a given order (harder to check systematically if we are
                       being consistent that way across the whole text). Note the numbering here is very simple
                       as we are only numbering these seg elements that occur within a given mod, not a running
                       numbering/ID throughout the file or the edition, which seems to me fine. -->
                     <!-- <transpose>
                        <ptr target="01"/>
                        <ptr target="02"/>
                     </transpose> -->
                     <transpose>
                        <ptr target="02"/>
                        <ptr target="01"/>
                     </transpose>
                  </listTranspose>
               </mod> –a more<lb/> various Composite. The beauty of the <lb/>drooping and sheaf-like
               head of the <lb/>rush all men have admired in all <lb/>ages–and it must have some
               such <lb/>near and unaccountable relation to <lb/>human life, as astronomy has to
               <lb/>those laws and figures which first <lb/>existed in the mind of man. <lb/>All the
